    line-height: 1.6;"><p>Grammar-Translation Method: In this traditional approach, the teacher is a source of input and a model for language learning. The teacher provides learners with a set of grammatical rules and vocabulary lists, which they must learn to translate sentences and texts from the target language into their native language.</p>
<p>Direct Method: In this traditional approach, the teacher takes on a supporting role and counselor. They use a communicative approach, whereby they speak only in the target language and prioritize developing speaking and listening skills. The teacher models the language for learners, but also encourages them to practice their language skills actively with one another.</p>
<p>Situational Approach: In this structuralist approach, the teacher serves as an authority figure in the classroom. They define and present certain language situations to learners, who then learn to use the language presented in those specific situations.</p>
<p>Audiolingual Approach: In this structuralist approach, the teacher is a facilitator of language learning. They provide learners with drills and exercises to help them practice the target language in a structured manner. The teacher serves as a guide and model, but also allows learners to work independently and in pairs to develop their language skills.</p>
<p>Cognitive Approach: In this generative-transformational approach, the teacher takes on a supporting role and counselor. They help learners recognize and understand the underlying structures of language and guide them in developing their own internal grammar rules.</p>
<p>Community Language Learning: In this humanistic approach, the teacher is a facilitator of language learning. They create a supportive and non-judgmental environment in which learners can freely express themselves in the target language. The teacher emphasizes the importance of collaboration and communication among learners to foster language acquisition.</p>
<p>Total Physical Response: In this humanistic approach, the teacher serves as an authority in the classroom. They create a series of commands and actions that learners must follow, helping them internalize the language through physical movement and repetition.</p>
<p>The Silent Way: In this humanistic approach, the teacher is a facilitator of language learning. They encourage learners to discover language patterns and rules on their own through problem-solving activities. The teacher provides only minimal input and models, allowing learners to take on the majority of responsibility for their learning.</p>
<p>Suggestopedia: In this humanistic approach, the teacher plays a supportive role and counselor. They create a relaxed and comfortable learning environment that encourages learners to stay positive, motivated, and focused. The teacher provides learners with a variety of non-traditional learning materials, such as music and art, to help them learn the target language.</p>
<p>Natural Approach: In this humanistic approach, the teacher is a facilitator of language learning. They create a natural and communicative learning environment in which learners are encouraged to engage in conversations and express themselves freely in the target language. The teacher provides learners with visual aids, body language, and context to help them comprehend the language. </p>
<p>Lexical Approach: In this alternative approach, the teacher serves as a facilitator of language learning. They focus on developing learners' vocabulary and collocations through exposure to authentic language materials. The teacher encourages learners to identify word meanings and word associations, and to develop a rich network of language knowledge.</p>
<p>Competency-Based Language Teaching: In this alternative approach, the teacher plays multiple roles as a facilitator, authority, and counselor. They set clear learning objectives and create a series of tasks and activities that learners must complete to demonstrate their language competencies. The teacher provides learners with feedback and support to help them achieve their objectives.</p>
<p>Communicative Language Teaching: In this communicative approach, the teacher plays a supporting role and counselor. The teacher creates authentic and meaningful communication situations that require learners to use the target language to communicate with each other. The teacher provides learners with feedback and support, encouraging them to continuously improve their language skills.</p>
<p>Task-Based Language Teaching: In this communicative approach, the teacher acts as a facilitator of language learning. The teacher creates a series of real-world tasks that learners must complete using the target language. The teacher provides support and guidance, encouraging learners to develop their language skills through active engagement in authentic tasks.</p>
<p>Content-Based Instruction: In this communicative approach, the teacher is a facilitator of language learning. The teacher creates lessons that integrate language learning with content knowledge in a specific subject area. The teacher provides scaffolding and support, helping learners build both content knowledge and language skills.</p>
<p>Cooperative Language Teaching: In this communicative approach, the teacher acts as a facilitator of language learning. The teacher creates cooperative learning activities that require learners to work together to complete tasks using the target language. The teacher provides support and guidance, encouraging learners to collaborate and build on each other's language skills.</p></div>

